{
  "$schema": "https://aka.ms/codetour-schema",
  "title": "2/3: From State to Pixels",
  "description": "Follow telemetry data from the IPC boundary through the preload bridge, into the Zustand store, through React hooks, and into rendered components. Introduces React concepts along the way.",
  "steps": [
    {
      "file": "src/preload/index.ts",
      "line": 1,
      "title": "The Preload Script",
      "description": "The preload script runs in a special context: it has access to Electron's `ipcRenderer` (to talk to the main process) but executes before the renderer's code loads.\n\nIts job: build a `bridge` object and expose it via `contextBridge.exposeInMainWorld()` (line 577). After this, `window.bridge` is the **only** way the renderer can communicate with the main process.\n\nThink of it as the public API between two worlds. When you want to add new functionality, you start here."
    },
    {
      "file": "src/preload/index.ts",
      "line": 194,
      "title": "Bridge Structure ‚Äî Events vs Commands",
      "description": "The `bridge` object has two patterns:\n\n1. **Event listeners** (like `onVehicleDelta` on line 195) ‚Äî register a callback on `ipcRenderer.on()`, return an unsubscribe function. These receive **pushed data** from the main process.\n\n2. **Command methods** (like `arm` on line 219) ‚Äî call `ipcRenderer.invoke()` and return a Promise. These **send requests** to the main process and await responses.\n\nThe `Bridge` interface (line 23) is the complete typed contract ‚Äî scroll up to see all ~40 methods. Events = data flowing in, commands = actions flowing out."
    },
    {
      "file": "src/preload/index.ts",
      "line": 195,
      "title": "The Telemetry Entry Point",
      "description": "`onVehicleDelta` listens for the `'vehicle:delta'` event that `ipcBridge.ts` pushes at 30Hz (Tour 1, step 12).\n\nIt wraps the raw Electron event handler in a clean callback pattern:\n- The caller passes a function `cb`\n- That function is called with the `VehicleDeltaPayload` every time new data arrives\n- The return value is an unsubscribe function to stop listening\n\nThis is the entry point for all telemetry data into the renderer process. Next, let's see what calls this."
    },
    {
      "file": "src/renderer/src/store/vehicleStore.ts",
      "line": 1,
      "title": "Zustand ‚Äî A Reactive State Container",
      "description": "**React concept: Zustand**\n\nBefore we look at how data reaches the UI, you need one React fundamental: React components re-render when their state changes. But \"state\" needs to live somewhere.\n\n**Zustand** is a tiny library that creates a global state object. Any component can subscribe to a slice of it, and when that slice changes, only subscribed components re-render. Think of it as a global variable with automatic change notifications.\n\n---\n\nThis file creates `useVehicleStore` ‚Äî a Zustand store that holds all vehicle telemetry for the renderer process. Its shape mirrors what comes over IPC: a `vehicles` map keyed by vehicle ID, each containing a partial `VehicleSnapshot`."
    },
    {
      "file": "src/renderer/src/store/vehicleStore.ts",
      "line": 24,
      "title": "Delta Merge into Store",
      "description": "When a delta arrives from the main process, `mergeDelta` shallow-merges it into the vehicle's existing snapshot.\n\nLine 28: `{ ...prev.vehicles[vehicleId], ...delta }` ‚Äî the spread operator means:\n- Start with all existing groups for this vehicle\n- Overwrite only the groups present in the delta\n- Unchanged groups **keep their existing object references**\n\nThis last point is critical for React's change detection. If the `battery` group didn't change, its object reference stays the same, so components subscribed to `battery` won't re-render.\n\nLine 33: `activeVehicleId: prev.activeVehicleId ?? vehicleId` ‚Äî auto-selects the first vehicle seen."
    },
    {
      "file": "src/renderer/src/store/vehicleStore.ts",
      "line": 58,
      "title": "IPC Wiring at Module Load",
      "description": "This block connects the IPC bridge to the Zustand store. At module load time, it registers three listeners:\n\n1. `onVehicleDelta` ‚Äî calls `mergeDelta()` on every 30Hz tick\n2. `onVehicleAdded` ‚Äî adds an empty slot for a new vehicle\n3. `onVehicleRemoved` ‚Äî removes a vehicle's data\n\nThe `setTimeout(..., 0)` defers registration to the next event loop tick. This ensures React has finished mounting before store updates start flowing in.\n\nThis is the connection point: IPC events from Tour 1 flow into the Zustand store here. From here, React hooks pick up the data."
    },
    {
      "file": "src/renderer/src/hooks/useVehicle.ts",
      "line": 20,
      "title": "useTelemetry ‚Äî Subscribing to a Group",
      "description": "**React concept: Hooks**\n\nA **hook** is a function starting with `use` that lets a component \"hook into\" something external ‚Äî in this case, the Zustand store. When you write `const battery = useTelemetry('battery')` inside a component, you're subscribing to the battery group. Whenever the battery group changes in the store, React will re-render that component with the new data. If attitude changes but battery doesn't, your component is left alone.\n\n---\n\n`useTelemetry` is generic over group name. The selector (line 24-27) extracts just one group from the active vehicle's snapshot. It returns `undefined` if the group hasn't been received yet ‚Äî components must handle this loading case."
    },
    {
      "file": "src/renderer/src/hooks/useVehicle.ts",
      "line": 79,
      "title": "JSON.stringify Stability Trick",
      "description": "Zustand compares selector results with `Object.is()` to decide if a re-render is needed. For object/array returns, a new object is created every call ‚Äî triggering unnecessary re-renders even when the data hasn't changed.\n\nThe pattern here:\n1. **Line 92**: The selector returns `JSON.stringify(result)` ‚Äî a primitive string\n2. **Line 94**: The component parses it back with `JSON.parse()`\n\nThis ensures the selector returns a **stable primitive**. The component only re-renders when the actual data values change, not when object references change.\n\nYou'll see this pattern throughout the codebase. Watch for it when debugging performance issues."
    },
    {
      "file": "src/renderer/src/App.tsx",
      "line": 44,
      "title": "React Root Component",
      "description": "**React concept: Components & JSX**\n\nA **component** is a function that returns JSX ‚Äî the HTML-like syntax you see below (e.g., `<div className={styles.root}>`). Components compose by nesting: `App` renders `FlyView`, which renders `BatteryStatus`, which renders `BatteryWidget`.\n\n`useState` (line 45) creates local state that persists across re-renders ‚Äî here it tracks which view (fly/plan/setup) is active.\n\n---\n\n`App` is the root. Line 48 checks if this window is a popout (via URL parameter). Line 55: `{view === 'fly' && <FlyView />}` is **conditional rendering** ‚Äî only the active view's component tree exists at any time."
    },
    {
      "file": "src/renderer/src/flyview/FlyView.tsx",
      "line": 29,
      "title": "FlyView ‚Äî Layout Composition",
      "description": "FlyView is the primary flight interface. Look at the sidebar section starting at line 243:\n\n```\n<VehicleSelector />\n<FlightModeButton />\n<ArmedIndicator />\n<AttitudeIndicator />\n<Compass />\n<InstrumentPanel />\n<GpsStatus />\n<BatteryStatus />\n<LinkQuality />\n```\n\nEach widget **independently subscribes** to its needed telemetry group via hooks. There is no \"prop drilling\" of telemetry data from FlyView down to children ‚Äî each widget fetches what it needs directly from the store.\n\nThis is a common pattern: the parent handles layout, children handle their own data."
    },
    {
      "file": "src/renderer/src/flyview/BatteryStatus.tsx",
      "line": 4,
      "title": "End-to-End: Battery Telemetry",
      "description": "This is the simplest complete example of the full telemetry data flow.\n\n- **Line 5**: `useTelemetry('battery')` subscribes to the battery group\n- **Lines 7-9**: Guard against no data (group hasn't been received yet)\n- **Lines 13-21**: Render each battery instance\n\nThe complete data journey:\n```\nAutopilot sends BATTERY_STATUS (msgid 147)\n‚Üí VehicleState._handleBatteryStatus updates battery group, increments seq\n‚Üí ipcBridge 30Hz tick pushes delta\n‚Üí vehicleStore.mergeDelta merges it\n‚Üí useTelemetry('battery') detects the change\n‚Üí BatteryStatus re-renders with new values\n```\n\nNo polling. No explicit refresh. The push-based architecture handles it automatically."
    },
    {
      "file": "src/renderer/src/flyview/BatteryStatus.tsx",
      "line": 26,
      "title": "Props ‚Äî Passing Data to Children",
      "description": "**React concept: Props**\n\nWhen `BatteryStatus` renders `<BatteryWidget voltage={bat.voltage} ...>`, it passes data as **props** ‚Äî read-only arguments to the child component. The child receives them as a typed object parameter (lines 27-35).\n\nThis is how data flows *down* the component tree. `BatteryWidget` doesn't know about Zustand or hooks ‚Äî it just renders what it receives.\n\n---\n\nThis separation ‚Äî **container component** (BatteryStatus, has hooks) and **presentational component** (BatteryWidget, just props) ‚Äî is a common React pattern in this codebase. The container fetches data; the child draws it."
    },
    {
      "file": "src/shared-types/ipc/events.ts",
      "line": 1,
      "title": "Event & Channel Name Enums",
      "description": "The `IpcEvents` enum defines all push event names (main ‚Üí renderer), while `IpcChannels` (in `channels.ts`) defines all request/response channel names (renderer ‚Üí main).\n\nUsing enums instead of string literals ensures a typo causes a **compile error**, not a silent bug. Both the preload and ipcBridge import these same enums.\n\nWhen debugging IPC issues, these two files are the lookup table: find the event/channel name, then grep for it in `ipcBridge.ts` and the preload to trace the full path.\n\n---\n\n**End of Tour 2.** You now understand the render path: how deltas cross the IPC bridge, merge into the Zustand store, flow through hooks, and render in components. Continue with Tour 3 to see the reverse direction ‚Äî user actions flowing back to the autopilot."
    }
  ]
}
